### Split intransitivity
While accusative and ergative systems encode S uniformly the same way as either A or P, in a number of languages this is not the case. Instead S is sometimes marked as A and sometimes as P, depending on the semantics of the verb, and whether the intransitive argument is perceived to be agent-like or not. Since the class of intransitive verbs is thus split, this system is called *split intransitivity* or *split-S* (see below for a discussion of terminology). A well-known example is Lakhota (see also the examples in section 1):[^lakhota2]

