Not all split intransitive languages are like Lakhota. On the one hand, [70--83][#dixon94;] distinguishes between *split-S* and *fluid-S* languages: While in the former type the choice of marking is fixed for each verb, according to the *prototypical* semantics, the latter allows SA and SO marking for the same verb, depending on the *situational* semantics or pragmatics; in such a language it may be possible, for example, to indicate the volitionality or degree of control that a participant possessed with respect to a particular event. Unfortunately, Dixon includes no clear examples of such languages. He mentions an Arawak language, Baniwa do Içana, that apparently exhibits this pattern; Baniwa do Içana is, according to Aikhenvald (??), the same language as Kurripako, which I discuss in section <!--\ref{kurripako}-->, but I found no clear indications of a fluid nature of the split in my source [#baure-kurri]. More convincing examples appear in [#mithun91;] (even though she does not use the term fluid-S). In Guaraní, some verbs may appear with either A or P marking; however this seems to indicate a shift in semantics rather than pragmatics (e.g. *mimí* translates to 'shine' when marked with A, but to 'be brilliant' when marked with P). More to the point might be Central Pomo; SP marking is apparently optional and only chosen if the speaker wants to highlight the affectedness of the participant.

